This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Wang Shuzhi, southern weekend staff writer

Editor in chief | Qian Haoping

More than 20 days to seek medicine "no door" , Li Yue alias feel powerless.

Her two-year-old son, who is epileptic and takes capram every day, is now in danger of going off his medication because of the new pneumonia outbreak.

Li Yue's family lives in Tufeng County, Huanggang City, Hubei Province, a hard-hit area. Wuhan "closed city" , she has been looking for various ways to buy medicine for her son, has not bought medicine, merchants can not send goods, express delivery, this makes her feel helpless.

While looking for medicine for her son, she joined a group of patients. There were more than 100 parents of children with epilepsy, they come from 12 regions in Hubei Province, including Wuhan, Huangshi, Suizhou, Xiaogan, Shiyan, Jingmen, Jingzhou, Huanggang, Tianmen, Xianning, Xianning and Xiantao.

In order not to let the child off drugs, parents to take a "self-help" approach, group contact the pharmaceutical industry to help procurement, and got the help of relevant volunteers. So far, volunteers have helped 12 of the sick children with the drug supply, while the rest of the children's parents have to wait.

1
No Help: drug returns

1

###No Help: drug returns

It was Li Yue's youngest son, who had a happy family, but after his birth, his life was changed.

When the child is two months old, have a sudden fall from the bed, at that time did not see abnormal, more than 10 days later all over convulsions. "fit up shiver all over, eyes up slope, mouth inside bubble. " Li Yue is very scared, holding his son went straight to Wuhan, to the city Children's hospital took two injections of Diazepam to calm down, but also was diagnosed with epilepsy.

The treatment of epilepsy mainly depends on drugs. Because of individual differences, some patients need to try different antiepileptic drugs to determine a treatment regimen. Most patients can control seizures with an antiepileptic drug, and if they relapse, they need to try different anticonvulsants, which can take months to figure out.

In the past two years, Li Yue's son has undergone two drug trials. At first, doctors at Wuhan Children's Hospital suggested she try Keppler, but she couldn't help it, so she added Oxcarbazepine to the list, "the results are more serious. " She then took the baby to hospitals in Shanghai and Beijing, the replacement of oxcarbazepine with depakine helped stabilize the condition.

According to the doctor's advice, the child needs to take the medicine for another seven to eight years. Seeing a doctor gradually put a heavy burden on the family. "It cost more than 100,000 yuan at least, " Li said.

On Weekdays, Li travels 80 km to the Wuhan Children's Hospital to buy Kipran, but can only buy two bottles of the prescription drug at a time, for 40 days.

Around January 23,2020, Li Yue heard the news of traffic control in Wuhan, immediately on the Internet to find medicine. After two days of review, most of the list was not successful, "basically can buy all the orders, some did not ship, some sellers heard to Hubei, the back order. ".

In order to find medicine for her son, she was "duped" by one of the largest pharmacies in the county, "He told me that people he knew in Wuhan could deliver the goods in three days from Wuhan. On the sixth day, he said the goods were still on the way from Guangzhou. Yesterday (February 13) I learned that the goods had not been delivered from Guangzhou either. He kept telling me that they were on the way. ".

On Feb. 5, Li finally found two parents who were willing to share the drugs online, but ten days after the delivery, it was still stopped in Zhengzhou and Guangzhou.

"At the moment, this drug is very difficult to handle, " Ms. Li said Feb. 14, the day after she learned from volunteers that JD.com had launched a platform to buy medicines for chronic diseases. However, when she tried to buy through the channel, merchants refused to take orders on the grounds that the destination was Huanggang, Hubei.

2
Take the risk: lengthen the medication cycle

2

###Take the risk: lengthen the medication cycle

Luckier Than Li, Ken Xie (not her real name) has received his son's medicine through "personal connections" , but has gone to great lengths.

Ken Xie, who is from Hanchuan, a county-level city under Xiaogan, lives in Changsha. Her 5-year-old son was diagnosed with epilepsy when he was 2.

At the end of 2019, the Ken Xie family returned from Changsha to Hubei Province for the Lunar New Year holiday, ready to take a thirty day dose. Unexpectedly, trapped by the new crown pneumonia epidemic, Hubei implemented a traffic control throughout the territory.

In the early hours of January 23,2020, Wuhan issued a notice saying that the city was "closed" . On January 25, the city's freeways were closed. On January 26, the city of Ezhou implemented a ban on motor vehicles.

Ken Xie is most worried about the January 28, Xiaogan City Administrative Village (community) , natural village traffic was cut off. Ken Xie's son's medication only lasted until Feb. 10, leaving her to consider the possibility that the boy could face withdrawal.

For nearly three years, her son has also been "testing" the drug, initially taking six months of Oxcarbazepine, later replaced by Depakine, and later added Topamax. Now, the child needs to take the medicine twice a day.

In the past, Ken Xie's son was given the dosage prescribed by his doctor. Only once, in her home in Changsha, did she forget to medicate her son, and the effect was immediate -- a dozen convulsions a day, "a twitch at a touch. ". Finally, she took her son to Xiangya hospital to get a sedative to ease the situation. After that, she never again dared to increase or decrease her dosage.

But after the siege, Ken Xie risked going on a drug cycle in order to keep the drug going longer.

On February 5, Ken Xie lengthened the interval from 12 hours to 14 hours and reduced the dose by 0.5 ml each time. This led to the unexpected occurrence of the child's hands and feet on the night of the abnormal shaking. Ken Xie was scared, so he went back to his original dosage.

Previously, she also asked relatives and friends who work at the Hanchuan Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine and the People's Hospital of Hanchuan to help find medicine, but both said they could not buy it in the city. "I even called 110, the municipal government, and the help-girl hotline of Hubei TV, but I couldn't. I was desperate. "

In an emergency, she asked two parents of sick children in Shanghai and Anhui respectively to help buy medicine, "I just wanted to do an experiment to see if I could get it, because there were some deliveries from SF express that had been sent back, and some that hadn't been delivered in over ten days, " Ken Xie said, beating his heart in order for his son's medicine to arrive smoothly, i called in a favor.

She thought she was in luck, and on February 9th, three days later, she received seven vials of anti seizure drugs -- enough to keep her son on for four months -- from Florida, Hunan, Anhui and Shanghai.

3
"drug stocks are changing by the hour. "

3

###"drug stocks are changing by the hour. "

Waiting for the drugs, on February 6, Ken Xie met more parents through a group of patients pulled up by the family's "flower mother" (screen name) . After seeing Hua's post, they began to join the group through social media on Feb. 6, hoping to find as many sources of drugs as possible and solve distribution problems.

As he entered the group, Ken Xie learned that some parents had given their children larger doses, causing seizures. "It's a chronic condition, you take it for a long time, you stop and it starts to happen, and over time it becomes a secondary tic, " Ken Xie said.

The patient group main flower mother is a Shanghai epileptic child's parent, she is engaged in the cerebral palsy rehabilitation popular science work many years, has the rallying point in the patient group. Out of the "sense of shame" , Hua mother usually rarely in real life to talk about the child's condition. But this time, she relented and sent parents'letters through Wechat.

After seeing the letter asking for help, Min Lei immediately responded. Min Lei, who works in the pharmaceutical industry, had no previous overlap with the group of children with epilepsy. By chance, she and the flower mother in the same hospital to see a doctor when the child met.

Min Lei contacted Dai Shenyi, the head of a medical company in Hangzhou, and Han Zhiyi, the founder of a medical APP. The two were recruited into a group of patients by Hua Ma and became volunteers. Together with more than a dozen other volunteers, they tried to help parents buy medicine.

Dai Shenyi was in charge of liaising with pharmaceutical companies and pharmaceutical platforms, while Han Zhiyi mobilized the support of his company's Wuhan Branch, Baozhongtang.

According to Dai Shenyi, epilepsy drugs belong to the central nervous drugs, which are under state control. Common antiepileptic drugs (such as Capram and Depakine) can be purchased in pharmacies by prescription, but they involve second-class psychotropic drugs (such as nitrazepam tablets) , must be in the hospital by prescription to buy, Wuhan Only Tongji Hospital, Wuhan Children's Hospital and other three-tier hospitals can provide. In addition, some of the children's family members choose to purchase overseas.

Since the outbreak of NCP, most of the antiepileptic drugs that parents can buy in China have only common types, and some parents are worried about the risk of being infected when they go to the hospital to prescribe drugs, and are unable to make a decision late, some parents bought foreign drugs from Daigou, but couriers were unable to enter Hubei Province.

During this period, volunteers from the medical industry such as Dai Shenyi played a role in drug procurement. They counted out the number of drugs actually needed to be purchased, and then "Baozhongtang" reported it to the Hubei Provincial Pharmaceutical Company, which distributed a certain number of drugs to "Baozhongtang" according to the stock situation of the major pharmacies in Hubei, finally through the EMS delivery to the hands of patients.

For Huang Hua, the boss of Baozhongtang, the job is not easy. "First, [ drug companies' ] inventory changes every hour, and second, patients in the urban area of Wuhan don't want to go to the hospital now, they buy medicine in the pharmacy. I went to the drug companies in the morning and got it. "

Since the outbreak of new crown pneumonia, many kinds of medical materials are in short supply in Hubei Province. For the province's drug store owners, the morning to go to the pharmaceutical company "Rob" supplies has become commonplace. Although epilepsy children's medicine is not as tight, but the situation is still tense.

Even if the procurement problem is solved, mailing is not easy. According to the regulations of the postal department, individuals who hand in scattered medicines shall submit invoices for the purchase of medicines and check them carefully before posting and delivering them. For long-term, large-scale and centralized delivery of drugs, the sender shall be required to provide the license of the drug production enterprise or business enterprise, as well as the identity certificate of the sender.

Affected by the new crown pneumonia epidemic, Hubei Province pharmaceutical companies have received a sharp increase in orders, "it is not possible to get so many invoices at once. " After constant consultations, Min Lei said, the first batch of drugs has been sent to all parts of Hubei, but only 12, totaling 48 items, total value: $4,677.

Only 12 children with the problem of drug use, not a lot of figures, "but demand has been increasing. " Min Lei also heard, jD.com health's recently launched "Hubei chronic disease patients to register" platform has received about 2,500 epilepsy drug registration information. She hoped that more people would be involved so that the problem of the sick child would be taken seriously.

4
The "last mile" puzzle

4

###The "last mile" puzzle

Min Lei is now worried about how the drugs can reach the parents of sick children, "many details are not well implemented, mainly the issue of delivery and the last kilometer of the problem. ".

Zheng Hui (not his real name) , of Ezhou, has yet to find a way to receive the drugs. "If we don't get there by March, they're going to be off their meds. "

Her 7-year-old daughter, due to serious illness, she not only let the child to take the drug produced in the mainland, but also tried the German-made Clobetazin and Taiwan's version of Josamide, the condition is stable.

Unable to directly buy imported drugs, Zheng Hui can only find the purchase of Guangdong Foshan to help. But after the outbreak of new crown pneumonia, Daigou told her that the postal service is no longer sent to Hubei Express. Zheng Hui panic, ask around how to buy medicine. Two days ago, she finally got back her daughter's home-made medicine, but still no news of the imported medicine.

She is one of a handful of parents still waiting. Some even walked to town to get medicine, but were persuaded to return.

Even though the Ministry of Transport of the People's Republic of China has issued an emergency transportation order since Feb. 8, and has repeatedly stressed the need to guarantee the delivery of epidemic prevention materials in Hubei, some parents have been denied the right to send medicine to their children.

Southern weekend on this call the postal express hotline 11183, said the operator, currently sent to Hubei Ems can still order, call the hotline address. In addition, if the mail to the countryside is less than 5 kg, it will be transferred to the village post office or the village committee. At that time, the post office will contact the addressee by telephone and inform the addressee to pick it up in time.

In response to the "last mile" problem, on February 11, the relevant staff of Hanchuan's new pneumonia epidemic prevention and control headquarters told the southern weekend that if they encounter difficulties in receiving express deliveries, they can help arrange for a courier to be delivered to the door by community officials.

Zheng, who no longer wants such "services, " is hoping to get her daughter out of Hubei by March. Li Yue had the same idea, thinking of her son's illness before, she was distressed, "even let me walk more than 10 kilometers to the county, or even 30 kilometers to the city, I am willing. "
